Title: Kestrel's Game
Source: V4
Act: II

===

~ The Alderman notices Fleur and sees opportunity. In the dungeon, Kestrel reads Silas in Fleur's training gaps — and plays both sides. She steers Fleur toward the fire the same way the war once steered her.

The Alderman notices Fleur. Not the demon — not yet — but the healing. The way she moves her hands. The half-gestures of someone trained in the old ways. He recognises witch-craft. And rather than burning her, he pauses. A child witch — young, desperate to help — is something he might use. He approaches her with a proposition: if she truly wants to help the people of the capital, she can do so under his protection. Access to the sick, the poor, even the prisoners in his dungeon. His real intention is to parade her before Kestrel — another turn of the screw on the woman who tried to murder him.

Fleur senses the trap. She consults the demon, who encourages her — reinforcing the feeling that she is protected, that she is special, that perhaps the prophecy has some truth in it after all. She accepts. The second shortcut.

In the dungeon she finds Kestrel.

Kestrel watches Fleur before she speaks to her. She clocks the lantern immediately. Then she watches how Fleur moves her hands — the half-gestures of someone trained in a discipline but not finished in it. Silas's methodology, unmistakably. Her reading is instant and bitter and wrong: Silas took the Book, found an heir, built a private lineage. The betrayal she has been living inside for ten years acquires a second layer. Silas didn't abandon everything when she ran. She abandoned Kestrel specifically — and kept going without her.

There is a moment — small and critical — where Kestrel almost breaks. She watches Fleur tend to one of the sick: slow, patient, precise. No fire, no demon, just the quiet work of someone well-taught in the discipline's foundation. It is unmistakably Silas. This is not the action of someone trained as an heir to a power base. This is someone who was loved. She does not stop. But the question has lodged.

She begins to see the gaps — specific absences, places where Fleur reaches for the next step and finds nothing there. Not ignorance. Deliberate, patterned absence — the kind that comes from a teacher who consistently pulled back at the exact moments the discipline demands a student push through. Kestrel doesn't have the full reading yet. She keeps moving.

The Alderman visits Kestrel. He comes to gloat. Kestrel, behind bars, makes her move. She tells the Alderman about the demon — frames it carefully: this is no ordinary witch-child, she carries a fire demon, she could be the Chosen One he has been searching for. The Alderman came to gloat about a killing. He leaves contemplating a coronation.

Now Kestrel works Fleur in earnest. She fills the space Silas left. She tells Fleur stories of the Order — selected and angled. She frames the demon as a tool of liberation. She tells Fleur that the ability she carries is exactly what the Order trained for. None of this is entirely false. That is what makes it effective.

Then she plays her deepest card. She tells Fleur the truth about Silas. The real version: Silas stole the Book of Demons from Kestrel in the middle of a war. She took it and ran. She abandoned her captain, her closest friend — to face the Alderman alone. Kestrel was captured because Silas fled.

Fleur defends Silas — argues that stealing the Book was an act of love, not betrayal. But the seed is planted. If Silas was capable of abandoning someone, maybe her refusal to teach the full discipline wasn't wisdom. Maybe it was cowardice.

For Kestrel, watching Fleur's face change, there is a near-breaking moment. She sees exactly what she is doing — stripping away restraint, feeding resentment, steering a good person toward destruction. This is exactly what the war did to Kestrel. She is doing to Fleur what the war did to her. For one beat, the cost of what she is doing almost stops her. It doesn't. She has waited ten years. She lets Fleur go.
